metadata.name: Bloc.Plan #2
metadata.description:
Working as an architect and interior designer daily, I always find that creating space is something interesting. Especially a block plan. As an architectural drawing, it serves to inform the viewer of the presence or absence of a space by composing positive and negative spaces on the site. Through this, I found out that block plan can be a captivating visual art as well.

Press [s] to save captured image

created using p5.js
dirbots - Aug22

metadata.name: Ligare #126
metadata.description:
Ligare doesn’t begin in the same form as it ends, its past shapes the whole of its being. I often find myself wrestling with composition in generative work, a friend of mine put it best: “it’s tough to think outside of a box you’ve created.”

If we saw stars only for what they are, there would be no constellations.


The piece makes use of fxparams, which asks you to join the creative process, follow your intuition, and find the form that *feels* best to you :)


After creation, each Ligare can be exported as a plottable SVG <3
Press ‘1’, ‘2’, or ‘3’ to change the size of the PNG output
Press ‘v’ to render the image as an SVG
Press ‘p’ to return to the PNG render instance

This piece is optimized to be plotted at 11x14” with a 0.5mm pen.
You may change the page dimensions and margin size, as well as pen size so that you can use different media if you choose to plot this yourself:

To change the page dimensions and margin size, press ‘w’ and adjust the url parameters by the inch.
Margin is changed by the hundredth of an inch, ex: 0.5in would be ‘marg=50’.
To change pen size, press ‘c’ and adjust the url parameters accordingly. Pen size is also changed by the hundredth of a millimeter, for example penSize=35 is 0.35mm.

Changing the page dimensions may alter the details of your output slightly, as the piece is meant to be displayed primarily with its default url parameters.

Created by Chris McCully using p5.js, p5.svg.js, and chroma.js
(2023)

metadata.name: Allégories booléennes #340
metadata.description:
"Allégories booléennes" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

This work is a continuation of research around the intersections of shapes that I have been exploring for a while. I wonder about the way in which they make it possible to bring out new compositions from superpositions of shapes that could initially represent a real disorder.

Controls:
• "a": Play the animation
• "s": Export the image (default 2160 × 3840px PNG)
• "h": Change export settings to high resolution (then press "s" to export a 6480 ×11520px PNG)
• "m": Change export settings to medium resolution (then press "s" to export a 4320 × 7680px PNG)
• "n": Back to 2160 × 3840px

Artwork by Julien Espagnon, 2022.

metadata.name: Snakeish! #28
metadata.description:
Snakeish! explores the realm of minimalistic abstraction.

The algorithm simulates a group of snakes attempting to navigate a grid, reminiscent of the classic Nokia snake game. When all the snakes become trapped, they transform into bold, vibrant lines.

The aesthetic leans towards minimalism, featuring strong color palettes and subtle texturing surrounding the snakes. The artwork is designed to be visually appealing in both large and small sizes.

This collection serves as a special gift for 'Summer Party' collectors, for many of them this will be their inaugural experience with a generative collection.

Enjoy the playful world of Snakeish!

Cheers,
Fernando.

metadata.name: Ceremony #38
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I’m so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. 🥂

Definitely check out “Forever” mode by tapping “F” or mouse click/tap — it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will “never forget” and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that’s a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses “…Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.” Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : “Forever” mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start “Forever” mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in “Forever” mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending “&density=2” (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.
